AI Resume Editor
Overview

The AI Resume Editor is a focused productivity tool designed to help job seekers tailor resumes to specific job descriptions. Instead of providing generic feedback, the application analyzes resume content against a target role and highlights alignment gaps, enabling users to iteratively improve relevance and clarity.

Timeline

Period: June 2025 – July 2025

Context: Master’s in Information Systems (United States)

This project was developed alongside graduate coursework, with an emphasis on applying AI systems to real-world decision support and productivity workflows.

Problem Statement

Many resume tools provide generalized suggestions without accounting for the specific requirements of a job description. This often leads to resumes that are well-written but poorly aligned with the role being applied for. The goal of this project was to reduce this mismatch by combining structured text analysis with AI-assisted rewriting.

What the Application Does

Parses resumes in PDF, DOCX, and TXT formats

Accepts a target job description as input

Compares resume content against role-specific keywords and skills

Identifies gaps in alignment and relevance

Suggests rewritten bullet points and summaries

Allows users to export a tailored version of the resume

The workflow is intentionally iterative, enabling users to refine content rather than rely on one-time, opaque suggestions.

My Role and Responsibilities

I designed and implemented the complete application flow, focusing on both user experience and system reliability. My responsibilities included:

Designing the end-to-end user workflow for resume analysis and iteration

Implementing AI-based text comparison and rewriting logic

Building the user interface and interaction logic

Integrating external APIs and managing data flow between components

Technical Design and Decisions

Frontend & Application Logic: Built using Streamlit to rapidly prototype and validate user interaction flows

AI Integration: Uses OpenAI’s GPT-4.1-mini model for structured text analysis and rewriting, selected to balance reasoning quality, latency, and cost efficiency

Backend & Data Handling: Python-based application logic with Firebase used for state management and persistence where required

No custom model training was performed. The focus was on prompt design, controlled generation, and reliable integration of AI services into a user-facing workflow.

Scope and Limitations

This project focuses on practical AI integration rather than advanced model training. The objective was to demonstrate how existing language models can be applied effectively to a specific productivity problem through careful system design, rather than through custom machine learning pipelines.

Why This Project Matters

This project reflects my interest in building tools at the intersection of user experience, system design, and applied AI. It emphasizes problem framing, iterative workflows, and responsible use of language models—skills that directly translate to frontend and full-stack engineering roles.

(Optional) One-Line Resume Version
AI Resume Editor: Designed and built a full-stack AI-powered application that helps users tailor resumes to job descriptions through structured analysis and iterative content refinement.

# Airline Performance Tracker — Operational Intelligence Dashboard (Power BI + Forecasting)

## Overview

The Airline Performance Tracker converts raw, fragmented flight performance data into a decision-ready dashboard that stakeholders can use to understand reliability, delays, cancellations, and trend behavior over time. The purpose of the project was not to “make charts,” but to build a structured analytics system that answers operational questions quickly and consistently.

---

## Timeline and Context

- **Period:** February 2025 – May 2025
- **Location:** United States
- **Context:** Master’s in Information Systems
- **Background:** SPSS exposure in early February 2025 influenced the move toward Power BI and dashboard-driven analysis.

---

## Problem Statement

Airline and flight performance data exists, but it is typically:

- large, raw, and inconsistent

- distributed across multiple tables / sources
- difficult to interpret without modeling and KPIs

Stakeholders struggle to answer questions like:

- Which airlines are most reliable?
- When do delays spike (month/year/season)?
- Which airports contribute most to delays?
- Are cancellations increasing over time?
- Can we predict trends, not just summarize history?

---

## Project Goal

Build an interactive, decision-ready dashboard that:

- cleans and models airline performance data
- defines and tracks aviation KPIs
- reveals patterns, seasonality, and trends
- supports decision-making with both descriptive and predictive insights

---

## Data Ingestion and Preparation (Foundation)

### Data Sources

- flight records
- delay and cancellation metrics
- airport and carrier metadata

### What We Did

- imported raw datasets into Power BI

- validated types (dates, numerics, categories)
- removed nulls, duplicates, and inconsistencies
- standardized airline and airport identifiers

### Tools Used

- Power Query (M language)
- Excel (initial validation)
- SQL-style logic for filtering and joins

**Outcome:** clean, analysis-ready data with consistent identifiers and reliable fields.

---

## Data Modeling (Making the Data Talk)

Instead of working with flat tables, the project used a relational model:

- **Fact table:** flights + performance metrics
- **Dimension tables:** airlines, airports, time

### Why This Matters

- faster queries and cleaner filtering
- accurate aggregations and totals
- scalable structure for future metrics
- KPI correctness (no “wrong totals” from messy relationships)

### Skills Applied

- star-schema thinking
- relationship design (cardinality, filters)

- analytical modeling discipline

**Outcome:** a stable analytics backbone that makes KPIs trustworthy.

---

## KPI and Metric Engineering (DAX)

This is where raw data became decision-grade insight.

### Key Metrics Created

- on-time performance %
- average delay duration
- cancellation rate
- flights per airline
- month/year trend measures
- airport-wise delay contribution

### How

- DAX measures
- calculated columns
- time-intelligence functions (trend and time-based slicing)

**Outcome:** consistent KPIs that can be reused across dashboards and filters without breaking.

---

## Visualization and Dashboard Design

The dashboard was designed as a workflow:
**Overview → Trends → Details**, not a cluttered chart wall.

### Visuals Used

- KPI cards for executive summary
- line charts for trend behavior over time

- bar charts for airline comparison
- heatmaps for airport congestion patterns
- slicers/filters for interactive exploration

### Design Focus

- executive-friendly layout
- minimal clutter
- clear information hierarchy
- interactivity for “one dashboard, many questions”

**Outcome:** a dashboard that answers operational questions fast.

---

## Advanced Analytics and Forecasting

The project intentionally went beyond “what happened.”

### Predictive Layer

Used Python (Pandas, NumPy, Scikit-learn) to:

- detect seasonal patterns
- forecast trend movement (e.g., delay trends over upcoming periods)

Results were integrated back into Power BI for visibility in the same decision surface.

**Outcome:** combined descriptive + predictive insights in one system.

---

## Insights Generated (What the System Could Answer)

By the end, stakeholders could consistently answer:

- which airlines perform best over time
- when delays spike (seasonality and trend behavior)
- which airports act as operational bottlenecks
- how cancellations and delays evolve year-over-year
- what trends to expect next (forecast layer)

This turned raw aviation data into operational intelligence.

---

## My Role

- structured the problem into measurable KPIs
- cleaned, standardized, and validated raw datasets
- built the relational model for accuracy and scalability
- engineered DAX measures for decision-grade reporting
- designed the dashboard layout for usability and clarity
- implemented forecasting workflow and integrated outputs into Power BI

---

## Tech Used

- Power BI (Desktop)
- Power Query (M)
- DAX
- Excel (validation)
- Python (Pandas, NumPy, Scikit-learn)

---

## Why This Project Matters

This project shows how I turn messy data into structured systems that drive decisions. It also informs how I design data-aware user interfaces later in my work—focusing on clarity, workflow, and correct metrics rather than “pretty visuals.”

# SLU Alumni Connect — Graduate Frontend Project

## Overview

SLU Alumni Connect is a web-based alumni engagement platform built during graduate coursework to centralize alumni, student, and administrative workflows into a role-based system with dashboards and data-driven views.

While academic in origin, the frontend was approached with production-grade discipline.

---

## Timeline and Context

- **Period:** August 2025 – December 2025
- **Location:** United States
- **Context:** Master’s in Information Systems
- **Status:** Completed as part of graduate coursework

---

## Problem Statement

Alumni information and engagement workflows were fragmented across spreadsheets, emails, and disconnected tools. This made it difficult to:

- track participation and engagement
- manage events and mentorship flows
- gain visibility into trends

The goal was to unify these workflows into a structured, usable system.

---

## My Role (Frontend Lead)

I led frontend development and translated requirements into usable interfaces:

- designed the frontend layout and structure
- built role-based dashboards
- implemented data-driven UI components
- integrated frontend views with backend APIs
- prioritized workflow clarity and usability by user type

---

## Frontend Architecture

- React + Next.js (App Router)
- component-driven dashboard layout
- reusable UI patterns for tables, metrics, and trend indicators
- role-based separation to avoid UI confusion across personas

---

## Dashboard and Data Presentation

Dashboards were designed to be decision-friendly:

- KPI-style cards for summary
- tables for detailed inspection
- visual cues for engagement patterns and trends

My earlier analytics exposure influenced how information was structured on the UI, with emphasis on readability and correct interpretation.

---

## Backend Integration (Context)

Backend services supported the frontend by providing structured data and enabling interactions (events, RSVPs, mentorship workflows). My focus remained on ensuring frontend components accurately reflected backend state.

---

## Deployment and Workflow

- deployed via Vercel
- version control via GitHub
- iterative refinement based on feedback and testing

---

## Scope Clarification

This project represents applied frontend architecture and data-driven UI design within an academic setting. It is not positioned as a large-scale production platform.

# Data & Analytics — Foundational Exposure

## Context

My exposure to data and analytics developed during my Master’s in Information Systems and supports how I design
interfaces and dashboards rather than representing a separate analytics specialization.

This knowledge influences how I structure frontend components that present and interact with data.

---

## Timeline

- **Period:** February 2025
- **Location:** United States
- **Academic context:** Master’s in Information Systems

---

## SPSS (Initial Exposure)

I first worked with **SPSS** as part of coursework focused on statistical analysis and data interpretation.

Through this work, I learned:

- How datasets are structured and cleaned
- How statistical outputs are generated
- How insights are derived from structured data rather than assumptions

The value of this experience was not the tool itself, but learning to reason about data systematically.

---

## Transition to Power BI

Working with SPSS highlighted a gap between analysis and communication.

To bridge this gap, I explored **Power BI**, focusing on:

- Building interactive dashboards
- Visualizing trends and comparisons
- Structuring data to support decision-making

Power BI aligned more closely with my frontend interests by treating visualization as a user-facing layer.

---

## How This Informs My Frontend Work

This analytics exposure directly affects how I build frontend systems:

- I design dashboards with awareness of what the data represents
- I prioritize clarity, hierarchy, and readability
- I treat UI as a communication layer between data and users

Rather than positioning analytics as a primary role, I use this knowledge to build **data-aware user interfaces**
that support real workflows.

---

## Scope Clarification

This experience does not represent advanced statistical modeling or data science work.

It represents:

- Foundational analytics exposure
- Tool familiarity
- Better-informed frontend and dashboard design
